 and formula berkshire hathaway is the fourth largest public company in the world and the th largest conglomerate by revenue berkshire is currently the th largest company in the sp  index by market capitalization and is famous for having the most expensive share price in the world with a class a share costing more than  each having never been split contents  history  corporate affairs  governance  succession plans  businesses and investments  insurance group  utilities and energy group  manufacturing service and retailing  clothing  building products  flight services  retail  media  real estate  other noninsurance  finance and financial products  investments  investment in apple inc  investments in us airlines  prior investments  subsidiaries and equity holdings  assets  see also  notes  external links historyedit berkshire cotton mills adams mass hathaway mills new bedford mass berkshire hathaway traces its roots to a textile manufacturing company established by oliver chace in  as the valley falls company in valley falls rhode island chace had previously worked for samuel slater the founder of the first successful textile mill in america chace founded his first textile mill in  in  the valley falls company merged with the berkshire cotton manufacturing company established in  in adams massachusetts the combined company was known as berkshire fine spinning associates in  berkshire fine spinning associates merged with the hathaway manufacturing company which had been founded in  in new bedford massachusetts by horatio hathaway with profits from whaling and the china trade hathaway had been successful in its first decades but it suffered during a general decline in the textile industry after world war i at this time hathaway was run by seabury stanton whose investment efforts were rewarded with renewed profitability after the depression after the merger berkshire hathaway had  plants employing over  workers with over  million in revenue and was headquartered in new bedford however seven of those locations were closed by the end of the decade accompanied by large layoffs in  warren buffett began buying stock in berkshire hathaway after noticing a pattern in the price direction of its stock whenever the company closed a mill eventually buffett acknowledged that the textile business was waning and the companys financial situation was not going to improve in  stanton made an oral tender offer of  ⁄ per share for the company to buy back buffetts shares buffett agreed to the deal a few weeks later warren buffett received the tender offer in writing but the tender offer was for only  ⁄ buffett later admitted that this lower undercutting offer made him angry instead of selling at the slightly lower price buffett decided to buy more of the stock to take control of the company and fire stanton which he did however this put buffett in a situation where he was now majority owner of a textile business that was failing buffett initially maintained berkshires core business of textiles but by  he was expanding into the insurance industry and other investments berkshire first ventured into the insurance business with the purchase of national indemnity company in the late s berkshire acquired an equity stake in the government employees insurance company geico which forms the core of its insurance operations today and is a major source of capital for berkshire hathaways other investments in  the last textile operations hathaways historic core were shut down in  buffett claimed that purchasing berkshire hathaway was the biggest investment mistake he had ever made and claimed that it had denied him compounded investment returns of about  billion over the subsequent  years buffett claimed that had he invested that money directly in insurance businesses instead of buying out berkshire hathaway due to what he perceived as a slight by an individual those investments would have paid off several hundredfoldcitation needed on june   it was announced that 